==English==
===Pronunciation===
*/kwĭvər/
*[kw̥ɪvə(ɹ)]
*:[[Rhymes:English:-ɪvə(r)|Rhymes: -ɪvə(r)]]

===Etymology 1===
Via Middle English and Old French from West Germanic *''[[kokar-]]'', whence also Old English ''[[cocer]]'', Old High German ''[[kohhar]]''
====Noun====
[[Image:Bow_recurve_quiver.jpg|thumb|right|150px|bow and quiver]]
{{en-noun}}

# {{cattag|Weapon}} A [[container]] for [[arrow]]s, [[crossbow]] [[bolt]]s or [[dart]]s, such as those fired from a [[bow]], crossbow or [[blowgun]].
#:'''Quotations'''
#:*'''1598''': Don Pedro: [[Nay]], if Cupid have not [[spent]] all his [[quiver]] in Venice, [[thou]] [[wilt]] [[quake]] for this [[shortly]]. Benedick:I look for an [[earthquake]] too then. &mdash; William Shakespeare, ''Much Ado about Nothing'', Act I, Scene I, line 271.
#:*'''1786''': Arrows were carried in [[quiver]], called also an arrow [[case]], which served for the [[magazine]], arrows for [[immediate]] use were [[worn]] in the [[girdle]]. &mdash; Francis Grose, ''A Treatise on Ancient Armour and Weapons'', page 39.

